%S A394678 0,1,5,7,19,35,41,63,80,99,109,143,155,195,224,255,271,323,341,399,
%T A394678 440,483,505,575,624,675,728,783,811,899,929,1023,1088,1155,1224,1295,
%U A394678 1331,1443,1520,1599,1639,1763,1805,1935,2024,2115,2161,2303,2400,2499
%N A394678 a(n) = (n! - 1) mod n^2.
%C A394678 Conjecture: Excluding the case a(4) = 7, when a(n) is a prime number, n is a prime such that n^2 - n - 1 is a prime (A091567). Verified for n <= 5*10^4.
%C A394678 By Wilson's Theorem, for a prime p, (p - 1)! == -1 mod p. This means that (p - 1)! = -1 + k*p for an integer k. Multiplying by p and taking the result mod p^2 yields p! == -p mod p^2. After subtracting 1, we get a result that is equivalent to stating p! - 1 == p^2 - p - 1 mod p^2.
%F A394678 a(n) = (n! - 1) mod n^2.
%t A394678 sequence[limit_] := Module[{fact = 1}, Table[(fact *= i; Mod[fact - 1, i^2]), {i, 1, limit}]]
%o A394678 (Python)
%o A394678 def sequence(limit):
%o A394678     sequence = []
%o A394678     fact = 1
%o A394678     for i in range(1, limit + 1):
%o A394678         fact *= i
%o A394678         sequence.append((fact - 1) % i**2)
%o A394678     return sequence
%o A394678 (PARI) a(n) = (n!-1) % n^2; \\ _Michel Marcus_, May 01 2026
